<div class="column-2 gridcol">
<p>In the early 1980s, when the AIDS epidemic first hit, those whose immune systems were ravaged by the strange new disease lived, on average, about six months.</p><p>Today, a 25-year-old man infected by what we now know to be the human immunodeficiency virus can expect to live an additional 53 years, a woman 58 years – an almost normal life expectancy.</p>
